title: For Sale:  H&K P2000SK with Night Sights and extra mags
postcontent: Like new, only fired two boxes through gun. I also have High-Cap mags that I will include if you are a LEO. Like the slightly larger P2000 model, the P2000 SK (subcompact) combines elements of the successful HK USP Compact pistol with recent technological innovations from HK engineers — only in a smaller, more concealable design. The P2000 SK is available with Law Enforcement Modification (also known as Combat Defense Action) trigger system introduced in 2001 on the USP Compact “LEM” (Law Enforcement Modification) model. This unique pre-cocked hammer system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull and short trigger travel from first to last round fired) with a double action hammer system. The LEM/CDA trigger pull has been reduced to 7.3 – 8.5 pounds of pressure (32.5 – 37.8 Newtons), compared to 12 – 15 pounds (53.4 – 66.7 N) found on many conventional double action pistols. Optional adjustment by an HK certified armorer can bring the trigger pull into the 5.5 pound (24.5 N) range. Using such an enhanced trigger system consolidates ease of use and safety into a convenient, innovative trigger operation — one that prevents unintended firing. And in case of an ammunition-related failure to fire, all that is needed is an additional second or third pull of the trigger without the need of first pulling the slide back to re-cock the Subcompact. The enhanced LEM/CDA trigger system combines the reliability of a double-action revolver trigger with the crisp, precise trigger of a single-action pistol. For shooters that prefer a conventional double-action/single-action pistol, a double-action/single-action variant is also available with a decock button mounted on the rear of the frame. A choice of two simple-to-install grip panels make it easy to custom-fit the P2000 Subcompact to any shooter’s hand. And the same ambidextrous magazine release and dual slide release levers found on the P2000 make handling the Subcompact easy for both right- and left-handed shooters. A set of abbreviated “industry standard” mounting rails on the P2000 SK enable lights, laser aimers, and other accessories to be added by sliding them onto the open rail system. The HK P2000 SK also can use widely available, reliable USP Compact magazines. If interested please call 604-9733

title: For Trade:  RARE Colt M1911 A1 (1943) National Match
postcontent:
RARE Colt M1911 A1 early model national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped to Springfield Armory in February of 1943. It was Issued to an enlisted serviceman at the time. (Trying to find out who it was issued to now through different channels.) There are specific clues on the gun that tell you who it MIGHT have gone to.. There is AA inscribed (Not stamped) on the ivory grips and on the frame Next to GHD. GHD is significant because Col. Guy H. Drewry inspected ordnance from June 17, 1942 to July 15, 1945 For COLT.

After having multiple collectors and Colt dealers at the gun show look at it. "AA" is believed to stand for "All American" 82nd Airborne. Which would match the dates the gun was issued, and the eagle carved on the Ivory grips. 82 Airborne was the first Airborne division in US Army history and had three major drops, made their first drop in July of 1943 to invade Sicily. Second was Salerno on 13 September 1943. The third was the invasion of Normandy Jun 1944.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. BUT NOT ALL PISTOLS BACK THEN WERE STAMPED WITH "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for Military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted National match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by a gunsmith. At some point it was re-blued, and fixtures were 24k gold plated and Ivory grips added. It has been determined the gold was added many many years ago as some has worn off in spots. Bluing and finish is still very nice... Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. I have put 100 rounds through it and drives tacks. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. 4,500$ cash obo.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta Tx4 Storm Semi Auto Tactical Shotgun 12 gauge
postcontent:
Compared to the Beneli M4.  From Beretta: The TX4 Storm is a gas-operated semi-auto tactical shotgun optimized for home defense. With a 5+1 capacity, flawless feeding of different loads, ghost-ring sights, a soft-recoiling mechanism and a short, maneuverable 18.5" barrel, it is perfect for its intended use right out of the box. 

The TX4 comes standard with a number of features highly prized by knowledgeable tactical shooters and law-enforcement professionals. The slim, elongated fore-end is ideal for quickly directing the barrel in different directions and moving it from target to target when negotiating tight spaces. The ghost-ring sights are designed for fast and intuitive target-acquisition, and the rear sight is removable should you want to equip the TX4 with the optics of your choice. For that purpose, a short Picatinny rail extends over the action, and will take a variety of tactical accessories without any modification.

One of the important features that sets the TX4 Storm apart from other tactical shotguns is that it reliably feeds and shoots loads of different power. Essentially, it is a semiauto shotgun that feeds as reliably as a pump: from mild low-recoil loads to full-power thumpers as well as slugs, the TX4 will keep cycling no matter what you feed it. Thanks to its self-regulating gas-operating system, the TX4 has a “smart” action that adapts itself precisely and efficiently to the load used without any adjustment on the user’s part. Also, the barrel is threaded for choke tubes (Optima-Bore HP and Optima-Choke HP choke tube system): the included choke may be easily replaced to tailor the shot pattern to the intended use.   Asking $1200 OBO please feel free to send offers the worst I can say is no. Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 Government .22 w/Threaded Barrel - Brand New in Box!
location: Woodruff, Spartanburg, Greenville, Greenville, South Carolina
postcontent:
Brand New! Colt 1911 Government .22 w/Threaded Barrel

The Colt Government Model 22 is built by Carl Walther in Germany, and imported into the US.

The Government Model 22 is blowback operated, having the barrel rigidly attached to the frame. Like the centerfire 1911, the Colt Government Model 22 has a thumb safety, grip safety, magazine release, and slide lock that operate just like the centerfire 1911. This makes this Colt 22 particularly a great trainer or understudy to the centerfire 1911, as it has the same solid feel of its big brother, with a crisp trigger pull, identical trigger reach, and the same manual-of-arms as the centerfire 1911.

This Colt is finished in an overall matte black, and has a long 1911 style trigger, but with some 1911-A1 features as well. The front and rear sights are dovetailed into the frame, to allow for windage adjustment, and many aftermarket sights are available, should a different style than the plain black sights be desired. Like the centerfire 1911, the slide locks open on an empty magazine. The Colt 1911 22 magazine holds twelve rounds of 22 LR ammunition. The thumb safety is on the left side for right-handed use, and the grip safety works just like on a standard 1911. The slide lock is also identical in operation to the centerfire 1911, as is the magazine release, so operating this 22 LR Colt will be familiar to anyone who knows how to run a centerfire 1911. Only the disassembly procedure is different, due to the fixed-position barrel of the blowback design.
